4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, the Alabama Indian Affairs
6 Commission has seven representatives from the seven
7 recognized Indian tribes, bands, or groups in the
8 state.
9 This bill would increase the number of tribes in
10 the State of Alabama that are represented on the
11 commission and recognize two additional tribes in the
12 state.
13 Under existing law, the commission may seek and
14 receive grants, funds, and other benefits from the
15 federal government.
16 This bill would authorize the commission to also
17 seek and receive appropriations and other funds from
18 the state.
19 This bill would provide that the commission may
20 not be compelled to provide certain tribal records to
21 membership organizations.
22 This bill would provide for the salary of the
23 executive director of the commission and set age and
24 residency requirements for the executive director.
25 This bill would also make nonsubstantive,
26 technical revisions to update the existing code
27 language to current style.
28
